b'[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)\n[Sufism](../../isl/index.htm#sufi)  [Index](index.htm)  [Previous](sok081.htm)\n[Next](sok083.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002B55PTI/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](img/tease.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Songs of Kabir_ , tr. by Rabindranath Tagore, intro. by Evelyn Underhill,\n[1915], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### LXXXI\n\nIII. 74. _pratham ek jo apai ap\n\n_\n\nIN the beginning was He alone, sufficient unto Himself: the formless,\ncolourless, and unconditioned Being.  \nThen was there neither beginning, middle, nor end;  \nThen were no eyes, no darkness, no light;  \nThen were no ground, air, nor sky; no fire, water, nor earth; no rivers like\nthe Ganges and the Jumna, no seas, oceans, and waves.  \nThen was neither vice nor virtue; scriptures there were not, as the Vedas and\nPuranas, nor as the Koran.  \nKabir ponders in his mind and says, "Then was there no activity: the Supreme\nBeing remained merged in the unknown depths of His own self." p. 128  \nThe Guru neither eats nor drinks, neither lives nor dies:  \nNeither has He form, line, colour, nor vesture.  \nHe who has neither caste nor clan nor anything else--how may I describe His\nglory?  \nHe has neither form nor formlessness,  \nHe has no name,  \nHe has neither colour nor colourlessness,  \nHe has no dwelling-place.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: LXXXII](sok083.htm)\n\n'